    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-02-11T05:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-02-11T05:30:00-05:00" n="913"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d913">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">846E.2395/2–1152: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Ceylon</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SJC1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Satterthwaite</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Colombo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-02-11T16:00:00+05:30"
                            >February 11, 1952—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>464. Views contained penultimate para <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss>
                    300, Feb 9<note n="1" xml:id="d913fn1">Department telegram 300, not printed,
                        reported that Ceylon Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_CSCS1"
                            >Corea</persName> had proposed on Feb. 8 that a rubber agreement be
                        enlarged to include U.S. assistance in procuring for Ceylon certain needed
                        materials including defense items. The Department expressed its belief that
                        the rubber contract should stand on its own feet and should be concluded
                        rapidly if Ceylon were really interested (846E.2395/2–952).</note> presented
                    to <gloss target="#t_PermSec1">Perm Secy</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_MEA1">MEA</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_MinFin1"
                        >MinFin</gloss>. <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> continues maintain
                    position (<gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 449, Jan 31)<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d913fn2">Not printed.</note> that rubber contract being discussed at
                    request <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> and therefore <gloss
                        target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> unwise to jeopardize agreement by insisting on
                    terms unacceptable to US.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_PermSec1">Perm Secy</gloss> said <persName corresp="#p_CSCS1"
                        >Corea</persName> had been instructed ask US undertaking assist <gloss
                        target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> procure development not defense forces items.
                        <gloss target="#t_PermSec1">Perm Secy</gloss> agreed contract shld stand
                    alone but said question wld be discussed by Cabinet tomorrow and he unable
                    instruct <persName corresp="#p_CSCS1">Corea</persName> without Cabinet auth.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_MinFin1">MinFin</gloss> said agreement enlargement sought as
                    means making contract more acceptable to Ceylon public and rubber trade and
                    expressed view that gen statement of US friendship and willingness assist in
                        <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> procurement problems wld fill
                    requirement. <gloss target="#t_MinFin1">MinFin</gloss> said he wld press Cabinet
                    to instruct <persName corresp="#p_CSCS1">Corea</persName> proceed immed with
                    negots. Principal Cabinet opposition apparently from Min Commerce and
                        Trade.<note n="3" xml:id="d913fn3">The Minister of Commerce and Trade,
                            <persName>Richard G. Senanayake</persName>, nephew of the Prime
                        Minister, <persName corresp="#p_SDS1">Don Stephen Senanayake</persName>, had
                        been in favor of expanding trade with China at the expense of commercial
                        ties with the United States. He was personally to lead Ceylon’s Delegation
                        to Peking in the fall of 1952 to negotiate the five-year rice rubber
                        agreement with China.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Satterthwaite</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
